    Using Linux

    Linux is a clone of UNIX. UNIX and Linux are very powerful operating systems and have been in use for over 40 years in the case of UNIX. Although Linux is a fully graphical operating system like Windows, a lot of the real power still resides with the command line tools; so it is useful to familiarise ourselves with it.

    Meet the shell

    The command-line in Linux is the shell. The shell is a program that takes keyboard commands and passes them to the operating system to carry out. The shell program in Linux is referred to as bash (Bourne Again Shell, an enhanced replacement for ‚Äúsh‚Äù the original UNIX shell program written by Steve Bourne). When using a graphical user interface we need another program called terminal emulator to interact with the shell, e.g. gnome-terminal, konsole etc. The Terminal emulator (a bit like the command prompt in Windows) can be found by clicking ‚ÄúActivities‚Äù and typing the first few letters of the software you are searching for ‚Äì in this case ‚Äúter‚Äù should suffice. You can find any piece of installed software like this. You can also pin frequently used applications to the sidebar for quick access. These are features of Ubuntu‚Äôs desktop which is a highly customised version of the software ‚ÄúGnome‚Äù3 and not inherent to EVERY Linux distribution.

  22. Click "Activities" and type the first few letters of terminal and start the terminal.
    23.  

    The first directory in the file system is called the root directory ( / ) The root directory contains files and subdirectories, which contain more files and subdirectories and so on. The root directory must not be confused with a directory called ‚Äúroot‚Äù. It is important to note that there are no "drive letters" such as "C:\" "N:\" etc. in Linux. Everything within the file system is located within the same hierarchy beginning at \, which is usually also the directory of the primary hard disc partition. Other partitions, and devices like pen drives can be mounted elsewhere within the file system e.g. /media/mypendirve. Do not worry about how to do this for now, when plugging in a pen drive in Ubuntu Linux this mounting task is done automatically for the user.

  23. In the terminal type 'ls' and press enter. This command is similar to dir from MS command prompt. It shows you the contents on the current directory.
    24.  
  24. You can enter paths as well. Try 'ls ..' and 'ls /'. The first is a relative path. It is the directory above. The second is the very top (root) of the harddrive. You can also use ls Desktop to show what is in the directory below the current working directory.
    25.  
  25. Type in pwd and press enter. It shows you your current working directory.
    26.  

    Changing the current working directory requires the use of the cd command. This must be followed by a pathname, the pathname of the desired working directory. A pathname is the route we take along the branches of the tree to get to the directory we want. Pathnames can be specified in one of two ways:
    1) As absolute pathnames, e.g. /usr/bin, root is represented by the leading slash
    2) As relative pathnames, e.g. start with a dot (.), or a double dot (..)

  26. Type in cd /usr/bin and press enter. Use pwd to confirm where you are in the filesystem.
    27.  
  27. Type in cd . and press enter. Use pwd to confirm where you are in the filesystem.
    28.  
  28. Type in cd .. and press enter. Use pwd to confirm where you are in the filesystem.
    29.  
  29. Type in cd - and press enter. Use pwd to confirm where you are in the filesystem.
    30.  
  30. Type in cd ~ and press enter. Use pwd to confirm where you are in the filesystem.
    31.  
  31. We can also change the format of the output to reveal more detail: Enter ls -l and then ls -al.
    32.  
  32. Use google to find the what these two commands do. Hint look for ls man page. Make sure you understand the permissions - for example what does -rw-r-r- mean?

    Installing Apache2 web server

    In Ubuntu we can install software from the command line from online repositories. The listing of which repositories are available are held in the file /etc/apt/sources.list First, we need to update our list of packages available to install Issue the commands sudo apt-get update (you‚Äôll be asked for your password as ‚Äúsudo‚Äù is asking to elevate your access level)

  44. Enter sudo apt-get install apache2 to install Apache (a web server)
    45.  
  45. Open firefox and put http://127.0.0.1/ in the address bar. You should see a default web page.
    46.  
  46. You can serve your own web pages by placing .html or .php files in the folder located at /var/www/html
    47.  
  47. Use the command sudo chmod 777 /var/www/html -R this will grant all permissions to the folder (don‚Äôt worry about this now ‚Äì the topic of permissions will be covered in the lectures)
    48.  
  48. Navigate to the directory: cd /var/www/html
    49.  
  49. Then type: touch text.htm. Followed by: gedit text.htm. This will bring up a text editor so you can create a web page. Once done save your page and navigate to it using Firefox
